A verified validator on taostats is not related to Finney. Staking (or delegating as it should be referred to) is a feature of the Finney network and will be available to all users. Taostats is a third party website providing data analytics and resources on tao, they have a service whereby they verify a validator (through a transaction they confirm that the cold/hotkey belongs to the entity verifying the validator) and then provide a directory of 'trusted/ verified validators with services being built on top of that for users such as alerts, notifications (and soon to be reporting, ability for validators to calculate validator shares for those pooling together not through delegation - and more as the needs and network expand).

There is no difference however in your ability to be nominated (delegated to) on the bittensor network. It is a services and marketing tool you make available to you users and helps delegators know more about you when making an informed choice as to whom to nominate to.

Currently around 35%. This is based on the current validator APR minus the 17.99% (referred to as 18%) validator commission set by the foundation.
The calculator on taostats ( https://taostats.io/staking/#staking-calculator ) uses an APR defined by todays current return/t which is calculated correctly using the metagraph data - 

HOWEVER, we do not take into account diminishing returns (as issuance of tao increases. along with % of total issuance staked, the returns go down), neither does it auto compound (this would of course course it to be higher than stated). We felt that as % of total stake was going to be an unknown variable (will go up as soon as delegating is available, but will also pull the other way as liquidity/volume on exchanges increases), it was safer just to give the returns at a given point in time and not make promises on future returns.

We do let you set the price of tao however, so you can play with what you will earn IF tao = xx

Staking has always been live. It’s “delegated staking” that will be enabled after Finney. For now, you can stake your Tao in a validator but you will need a) to register a hotkey which is costly and time consuming and b) to have 1,024t or more staked to this key to remain registered. After Finney, people will be able to delegate their Tao (without minimums) to other people’s validators and receive rewards, minus an 18% tax that goes to the validator.
Hi Actually how many time is necessary for register the hotkey (validator).

Not sure what you mean. You register a key only once to be part of the network. After that, you need to either have a competitive miner or a validator with a large stake to remain registered. If you get de-registered, you need to start the registration process again.

I have already my hotkey and coldkey + 1024 TAO.
I want to be validator.
But I need register my hotkey. How many time is the process?

It depends on POW difficulty and your setup. You need multiple GPUs to register and normally it will take days or weeks, depending on your hash power and luck. As it stands, you are probably better off waiting for Finney and then delegate your Tao to another validator while you are waiting for registration of your own hotkey to happen. And this assuming you have enough Tao to stay registered in Finney (the threshold will probably be much more than 1,024 as there will be fewer validators). Frankly, you may be better off just delegating.

Yes, there is a page with all verified validators on https://taostats.io/verified-validators/ which shows you all validators who have verified themselves and established a proof of trust and ownership over their UID. Currently you can then click through to the validator page and read a bit more about what they do, follow their various links and make your own due diligence.

There will be a big update to this page over the weekend to bring things in line with Finney launch which will show the stake, delegations, and more relevant information and once Finney is live we will have a big week of advancements to this part of the site (along with some other surprises).

I should of course state that not all validators who want your delegation choose to verify with taostats and you will be able to find other options through twitter and other channels. It is not our position to comment on the financial models employed by validators (I may personally have an opinion if you ask but it will not effect the stance of taostats) - and we will always show the 'true' 17.99% commission being charged by the chain on taostats - which means you will need to look into the various options that are more financially rewarding yourself. This is because we believe it is more important to value validators by what they are doing, rather than a % point.
